               <msContents>
                  <summary>Qānūn al-nisā’ </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_338-item1">
                     <author ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305973866/" key="person_305973866">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Author unknown</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7280">Qānūn al-nisā’</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7280">قانون النساء</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">اما بعد این رسالۀ است در باب آداب واطوار زنان</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">تمام شد کتاب قانون النساء خط خام اصالتعلی
                        بهاری</explicit>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <colophon>f.55a</colophon>
                     <note>
                        <p> This short risāla shows substantial similarities with
                              <persName>Khvānsarī’s</persName> ʿAqāʾid al-nisāʾ, including passages
                           that appear to have been lifted in their entirety from that work. The
                           chapter headings listed at the beginning are as follows, although they do
                           not correspond completely to the contents of the MS: Chapter One: On what
                           women consider necessary; Chapter Two: On their form of orthodoxy;
                           Chapter Three: On their fasting days; Chapter Four: On wedding nights and
                           the practices of brides and grooms; Chapter Five: On the things that
                           women consider offensive at certain times; Chapter Six: On pregnancy;
                           Chapter Seven: On attending the bath house; Chapter Eight: On singing and
                           playing various instruments; Chapter Nine: On the dishes which women
                           prepare for nazr etc.; Chapter Ten: On the interaction of women, their
                           husbands, and their husbands’ families; Chapter Eleven: On the devices
                           which women employ to keep the evil eye at bay; Chapter Twelve: On
                           intimates and strangers; Chapter Thirteen: On women’s prayers; Chapter
                           Fourteen: On welcoming and saying goodbye to guests; Chapter Fifteen: On
                           the terms that women devise for friends and extended family; Conclusion:
                           ‘On some miscellaneous topics’. </p>
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
